Kafka comes with .bat files inside the bin\windows folder, so you’ll be running commands in PowerShell or Command Prompt.
---

Step 1: Extract Kafka

Unzip the Kafka file (e.g., kafka_2.13-3.5.0.tgz) using 7-Zip or WinRAR.

Move the extracted folder somewhere easy, like:

C:\kafka
---

Step 2: Start Zookeeper

Kafka still needs Zookeeper (unless you configure KRaft mode).
Open PowerShell → go inside your Kafka folder:

cd C:\kafka
.\bin\windows\zookeeper-server-start.bat .\config\zookeeper.properties

Keep this window open.
---

Step 3: Start Kafka Broker

Open a new PowerShell window, then run:

cd C:\kafka
.\bin\windows\kafka-server-start.bat .\config\server.properties

Keep this window open too. Now Kafka is running on localhost:9092.
---

Step 4: Create a Topic

Open a new PowerShell window and run:

cd C:\kafka
.\bin\windows\kafka-topics.bat --create --topic test-topic --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --partitions 1 --replication-factor 1

Check if it exists:

.\bin\windows\kafka-topics.bat --list --bootstrap-server localhost:9092
---

Step 5: Produce Data (Send Messages)

Still in PowerShell:

cd C:\kafka
.\bin\windows\kafka-console-producer.bat --topic test-topic --bootstrap-server localhost:9092

Now type a few messages and hit Enter after each one.
---

Step 6: Consume Data (Read Messages)

Open another PowerShell window:

cd C:\kafka
.\bin\windows\kafka-console-consumer.bat --topic test-topic --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --from-beginning

You’ll see all the messages you typed appear here in real-time.
---
Producer → Topic → Consumer
